1

00:00:01,139  -->  00:00:05,064
Now that you've seen how to fit a linear model in Python,

2

00:00:05,065  -->  00:00:09,470
it's important that you can interpret the results that you obtain from the line you fit.

3

00:00:09,470  -->  00:00:12,250
You might have noticed that the summary of the linear model

4

00:00:12,250  -->  00:00:15,474
you retrieve from Python gave a lot of information.

5

00:00:15,474  -->  00:00:17,530
Information in this portion,

6

00:00:17,530  -->  00:00:19,200
we will discuss soon enough.

7

00:00:19,199  -->  00:00:22,285
But for right now, let's look at this part of the results.

8

00:00:22,285  -->  00:00:25,920
Right here, is an area that tells us about the model we fit.

9

00:00:25,920  -->  00:00:29,965
Specifically, this is the intercept, and this is the slope.

10

00:00:29,964  -->  00:00:32,500
We can build a linear model in this way.

11

00:00:32,500  -->  00:00:40,840
The predicted house price is equal to 9,588 plus 348 times the area of the house.

12

00:00:40,840  -->  00:00:44,130
So if somehow, a home had an area of zero,

13

00:00:44,130  -->  00:00:48,700
we would predict that the model would cost 9,588.

14

00:00:48,700  -->  00:00:51,850
For every one unit increase in the area,

15

00:00:51,850  -->  00:00:55,814
we would predict that the price would increase by 348.

16

00:00:55,814  -->  00:00:58,772
If the units on the price were dollars and on

17

00:00:58,773  -->  00:01:02,595
your area were feet then the units here would match.

18

00:01:02,594  -->  00:01:05,289
You will want all the data in a single column to

19

00:01:05,290  -->  00:01:08,350
have the same units for your analysis to work correctly.

20

00:01:08,349  -->  00:01:11,019
Additionally, these here are the 'P' values.

21

00:01:11,019  -->  00:01:15,849
In regression, 'P' values are always given for testing if the parameter for

22

00:01:15,849  -->  00:01:21,424
the intercept or the slope are equal to zero and the null hypothesis, like this.

23

00:01:21,424  -->  00:01:24,484
Then in the alternative, by default,

24

00:01:24,484  -->  00:01:28,944
Python and other software compute 'P' values using a not equal to.

25

00:01:28,944  -->  00:01:32,529
These 'P' values can give a quick glimpse as to whether or not

26

00:01:32,530  -->  00:01:36,344
a particular variable is useful for predicting the response.

27

00:01:36,344  -->  00:01:40,734
The 'P' value here on the intercept isn't as useful as this one here,

28

00:01:40,734  -->  00:01:46,569
which suggests that the area is statistically significant in relating to the price.

29

00:01:46,569  -->  00:01:49,479
This will become more useful in the next lesson when we

30

00:01:49,480  -->  00:01:52,439
look at many of these coefficients all at the same time.
